<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05005e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05005e">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05005e"> 5(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 8 deer, 1 fawn &amp; 1 white bird / clerics Benignus booksatchel</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[King Laeghaire]</font> determined to make another attempt on the Saint&apos;s life, so with this design he posted men on all the roads which led from Slane to Tara. The Saint, to whom God had revealed the king&apos;s intention, took eight of his <mark>clerics</mark> and the boy <mark>Benignus</mark> to bear him company, and having blessed them, set out on his way; and the soldiers of the king saw nothing but <mark>eight deer</mark> followed by a fawn passing them along the mountain. &hellip; <font color="green">[182n1]</font>: In the <cite>Lebher Brecc</cite> (Whitley Stokes, Trans., p.25) the words are &ldquo;<mark>one fawn with a white bird on its shoulder</mark>&mdash;that is, <mark>Benen with Patrick&apos;s book-satchel</mark> on his back&rdquo;. <small> William Bullen Morris, <a name="WBML" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WBML"><cite title="source">The Life of Saint Patrick Apostle of Ireland</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1890) 181-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
